"The trees are greenhistory of New Zealand dates back at least 700 years to when it was discovered and settled by Polynesians, who developed a distinct Māori culture centred on kinship links and land. The first European explorer to sight New Zealand was Dutch navigator Abel Tasman on 13 December 1642. In 1840, the Treaty of Waitangi was signed, an agreement between the British Crown and Maori. It established British law in New Zealand and is considered New Zealand’s founding document and an important part of the country's history. The building where the treaty was signed has been preserved.",
"New Zealand was the first country to give women the vote. Nowhere in New Zealand is more than 128 km (80 miles) from the sea. It is an island (two to be precise) and rather long and slender. The result of that is you are never more than an hour or two from the sea, no matter where you are. You could be skiing in the Southern Alps and splashing in the ocean in the same day. New Zealand has the world’s largest hot water spring. Frying Pan Lake near Rotorua. New Zealand has the southern most vineyards in the world. New Zealand contains more bookstores and golf courses per head of population than any other country.",
"New Zealand has the world’s longest English language place name: Taumatawhakatangihangakoauauotamateapokaiwhenuakitanatahu. Roughly translated it means “The summit where Tamatea, the man with the big knees, the climber of mountains, the land-swallower who travelled about, played his nose flute to his loved one.” It is locally known as Taumata."
